      <hedline>
        <hl1>A Quieter Call to Action?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Elisa Vicari letter on Gretchen Morgenson's December 25 column on new proxy statement rules proposed by Securities and Exchange Commission</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Severance Pay Doesn't Go Better With Coke'' (Gretchen Morgenson, Dec. 25), which showed the potential power of shareholder proposals at companies:</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Severance Pay Doesn't Go Better With Coke'' (Gretchen Morgenson, Dec. 25), which showed the potential power of shareholder proposals at companies:</p>
        <p>The column made me wonder, however, whether a new Securities and Exchange Commission proposal might signal a silencing of the shareholder voice. Under the proposal, a company would be able to post proxy materials on the Internet as an alternative to mailing them, if it first notified shareholders how to find them.</p>
        <p>But will shareholders vote without the powerful call to action that is inspired by the appearance of the proxy materials in their mailboxes? Will corporate governance suffer in the name of saving a relatively small expense for companies?</p>
        <p>Elisa Vicari  East Northport, N.Y., Dec. 28</p>
      </block>
